Mean Square Displacement

For this part, I used one particle located at the center of the system and only is having Brownian noise.
The form to calculate MSD is as follows:
Where N is the number of particles, in this case 1, and as it can be seen that it is always comparing with the initial position, and of course, we are summing the across the number of particles, but for this case, the number of particles is 1, so we can program the following:

for i = 1:N
	diff = x[i, :] - x[1, :]
	msd[i] = sum(diff .^2)
end

With this we can obtain the MSD of one particle in the system, and comparing with the result of the theory with a Temperature of 273K, we obtain the following behavior:
